  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's a real, tangible burden that affects people like me who've spent years working with wires and circuits. Growing up in a small town near Kansas City, I never really had the chance to dive into advanced science classes, but my parents' educational backgrounds gave me some foundation. Now, as a self-employed electrician, I've seen firsthand how stereotypes about who belongs in tech fields can hold people back. When I explain my work to clients, I often get asked if I'm 'smart enough' to do electrical work, a question that cuts deep for someone who's been struggling with self-doubt. My depression makes this especially hard—I worry about being judged as 'not cut out for this.' Stereotype threat isn't just about women or people of color; it's about anyone who feels their identity might clash with a field they're trying to excel in. The good news is, addressing it isn't about fixing the problem but creating spaces where people feel safe to try without fear of failure. For instance, I've started mentoring young girls in my community through our local knitting and painting groups—using hands-on projects to show that technical skills aren't just for boys or people with fancy degrees. It's about building confidence through practical experience, not just theory. We need to shift the narrative so that being a woman in STEM isn't a barrier but a strength, and that's something we can do together, even in small ways.",
